1. Automate screenshot saving with Docker:

Create a new directory `screenshots` inside the `test_suite` directory and add the following `Dockerfile` inside it:
```dockerfile
FROM scratch

# Copy the screenshots directory from the container
COPY --from=<your-image-name> /screenshots /screenshots

# Install FTP server
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y vsftpd

# Configure FTP server
RUN mkdir /var/run/vsftpd.lock
RUN echo "anonymous:ftpuser@localhost:*:10000:10000,ftpuser:x:1000:1000::/home/ftpuser,ftpuser:ftpuser:1000:1000::/home/ftpuser" > /etc/vsftpd.user_list
RUN echo "anonymous_enable=NO" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
RUN echo "listen=YES" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
RUN echo "pasv_enable=NO" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
RUN echo "write_enable=YES" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
RUN echo "local_root=/home/ftpuser" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
RUN echo "chroot_local_user=ftpuser" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
RUN echo "force_local_user=ftpuser" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
RUN echo "connect_from_port_20=YES" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
RUN service vsftpd restart

# Copy the screenshots to the FTP server
COPY . /home/ftpuser

# Set the working directory for the FTP server
WORKDIR /home/ftpuser

# Expose the FTP server port and map it to the host machine
EXPOSE 2121

# Map localhost:2121 to the Docker container
CMD ["vsftpd"]
```
Replace `<your-image-name>` with the name of your base Docker image.

Now, build the FTP server container using the following command:
```
docker build -t screenshots .
```
Now, when your test runs, the screenshots will be saved in the `screenshots` directory.

Finally, modify the `Dockerfile` in the `test_suite` directory to mount the `screenshots` directory from the host machine:
```dockerfile
FROM <your-image-name>

# Mount the screenshots directory from the host machine
VOLUME ["screenshots"]

# Copy the Cypress test suite code
COPY . /usr/src/app
WORKDIR /usr/src/app

# Run Cypress test suite
CMD ["npm", "run", "test"]
```
Replace `<your-image-name>` with the name of your base Docker image.

Now, when you run your tests using Docker, the screenshots will be saved in the `screenshots` directory on your local machine.

